probably a combination of all three! the storm is expected to loose steam near the coast and typically they can migrate several miles in both directions (sort of like a wobble) before picking up speed again this could enhance rainfall over certain areas

this isnt out of the question as hurricanes tend to intensify over warmer waters and in areas of less shear (related to wind speeds aloft) however the angle of travel and the area it is traveling through isnt the best region to see conditions like that

thanks for the great questions! to finish things off wed like to remind everyone to stay #weatheraware during #florence find a trusted source and stay tuned for constant updates a good web resource is our new tropical weather forecast page:   #nwslivepictwittercomw7de6sqgy9
yes however talking with your landowners or neighbors may give you a better idea about the hazards that may exist at your location or with your home!

this is certainly a possibility if so the probability for damaging winds may slide northward along with the axis of heaviest rainfall right now the speed (and the fact that the storm looks to stall for 2436 hours near the coast) will be the other key factor
areas further southeast across central #ncwx will likely see higher wind speeds and more rainfall #nwslive  …
highest winds (25 - 35mph) with higher gusts arrive friday afternoon and persist through saturday evening further south = calmer windsshorter duration very track dependent
will vary but plan on sustained winds to peak in the 25 - 35mph range frisat with higher gusts possible

with saturated grounds (pre storm and during the storm) and gusty winds power outages are a real threat throughout much of central #ncwx more likely southeast vs northwest but isolated to scattered outages possible area wide periodicity unknown #nwslive  …

here are the "key take-home points" related to our mid-day #florence briefing in short even with forecast modification central #ncwx will have impacts from this storm have plans in place by mid-day thursday and prepare for the possibility of weather disruptions #nwslivepictwittercomv6ocqyz9db

here is the "earliest reasonable arrival time of tropical storm force winds" in other words there is a reasonable likelihood that 39+ mph winds will begin across central #ncwx by thursday afternoon have preparations completed #nwslivepictwittercomzkl07yao2n

a special reminder the forecast cone depcits the likely track of the center of the storm impacts are often felt outside in this case impacts in the form of 20 - 30mph winds with higher gusts and 3 - 7 inches of rain (or more) will be possible in durham! #nwslive  …

while the latest forecast trends has #florence moving south of our area significant rainfall remains possible for all areas of #ncwx with the track remaining uncertain dont focus on specific numbers! prepare for the worst and hope for the best! #nwslive  …
